==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Gullet
<hw>Gul"let</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>golet</ets>,
OF. <ets>Goulet</ets>, dim. of <ets>gole</ets>, <ets>goule</ets>,
<ets>throat</ets>, F. <ets>gueule</ets>, L. <ets>gula</ets>; perh. akin
to Skr. <ets>gula</ets>, G. <ets>kenle</ets>; cf. F. <ets>goulet</ets>
the neck of a bottle, <ets>goulotte</ets> channel gutter. Cf.
<er>Gules</er>, <er>Gully</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld>
<def>The tube by which food and drink are carried from the pharynx to
the stomach; the esophagus.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Something shaped like the food passage, or
performing similar functions</def>; as: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A channel for
water.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Engin.)</fld> <def>A preparatory cut or
channel in excavations, of sufficient width for the passage of earth
wagons.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>A concave cut made in the teeth of some
saw blades.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 658 --></p>

<p><ent>Gulleting</ent>⟦br⟧
